5648", "indices": [280, 303], "media_key": "3_2065176740398235648", "media_results": {"result": {"media_key": "3_2065176740398235648"}}, "media_url_https": "https://pbs.twimg.com/media/HKj7TbnWAAAaAK8.jpg", "original_info": {"focus_rects": [{"h": 470, "w": 839, "x": 0, "y": 0}, {"h": 470, "w": 470, "x": 0, "y": 0}, {"h": 470, "w": 412, "x": 0, "y": 0}, {"h": 470, "w": 235, "x": 35, "y": 0}, {"h": 470, "w": 870, "x": 0, "y": 0}], "height": 470, "width": 870}, "sizes": {"large": {"h": 470, "resize": "fit", "w": 870}, "medium": {"h": 470, "resize": "fit", "w": 870}, "small": {"h": 367, "resize": "fit", "w": 680}, "thumb": {"h": 150, "resize": "crop", "w": 150}}, "type": "photo", "url": "https://t.co/wtuwAZjfza"}]}, "favorite_count": 0, "favorited": false, "full_text": "China’s export controls on indium phosphide are creating a new bottleneck for AI data center expansion worldwide. The material is essential for high-speed optical chips that use photonics to move data through fiber instead of copper, a technology companies are racing to adopt as https://t.co/wtuwAZjfza", "id_str": "2065176744215138311", "is_quote_status": false, "lang": "en", "possibly_sensitive": false, "possibly_sensitive_editable": true, "quote_count": 0, "reply_count": 0, "retweet_count": 0, "retweeted": false, "user_id_str": "1092889720181407745"}, "note_tweet": {"is_expandable": true, "note_tweet_results": {"result": {"entity_set": {"hashtags": [], "symbols": [], "timestamps": [], "urls": [], "user_mentions": []}, "id": "Tm90ZVR3ZWV0OjIwNjUxNzY3NDQwNTU2NzY5Mjg=", "text": "China’s export controls on indium phosphide are creating a new bottleneck for AI data center expansion worldwide. The material is essential for high-speed optical chips that use photonics to move data through fiber instead of copper, a technology companies are racing to adopt as AI workloads outpace traditional electrical interconnects. Beijing began restricting InP shipments in February 2025, and delays in export licenses have already rippled through the supply chain. Coherent, a Nvidia-backed chipmaker, flagged shortages in May, and CEO Jim Anderson raised the issue directly with U.S. officials during Trump’s recent trip to China. With China producing about 70% of global indium, the restrictions give Beijing leverage similar to its earlier rare earth curbs.

The impact is showing up in price and availability. A 6-inch InP wafer has jumped 250% to around $5,000 since the controls started, and suppliers like AXT report a backlog of orders due to permit delays. Lumentum says it’s sold out through 2028 despite quadrupling output, while Taiwanese substrate makers have faced disruptions from the same permit issues. Nvidia has responded by investing $2 billion each into Coherent and Lumentum, and Marvell bought Celestial AI to secure photonics capacity, but analysts say InP is now one of several upstream constraints gating data center buildouts. U.S. officials have discussed the issue with China in Seoul and Washington, but China’s commerce ministry hasn’t commented publicly on easing the restrictions.

- World Business News."}}}, "rest_id": "2065176744215138311", "source": "<a href="http://twitter.com/download/iphone" rel="nofollow">Twitter for iPhone</a>", "unmention_data": {}, "views": {"count": "31", "state": "EnabledWithCount"}}

text:
@ren_stocks $SNDK and $MU are my winners and I see a long way up still. 

However, the photonics are getting sexier. 

Would you rotate?

